<p>This is the example code provided by first to get chassis Speeds from a field relative. Where or could I insert this into my existing drive train for it to function properly? Also I thought pathplanner handled most of this programming itself and desired angle and mps was calculated by it and not through command based code as mentioned in the example.</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":17,"updated_at":"2025-03-24T20:27:27.498Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":75,"readers_count":74,"score":15.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":496691,"topic_slug":"how-do-you-use-pathplanner-when-you-have-mecanum-wheels","display_username":"Kirby Caldwell","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":54537,"username":"loganbachman","name":"Logan Bachman","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/l/f6c823/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":72110,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programmer/Technician"},"post_url":"/t/how-do-you-use-pathplanner-when-you-have-mecanum-wheels/496691/9","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3567389,"name":"Kirby Caldwell","username":"KirbyC_1","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/k/a87d85/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-03-24T21:09:44.396Z","cooked":"<p>Pathplanner docs states</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Blockquote</p>
</blockquote>
<ul>
<li><code>getPose</code> - Returns the current robot pose as a <code>Pose2d</code></li>
<li><code>resetPose</code> - Resets the robot’s odometry to the given pose</li>
<li><code>getRobotRelativeSpeeds</code> or <code>getCurrentSpeeds</code> - Returns the current robot-relative <code>ChassisSpeeds</code>. This can be calculated using one of WPILib’s drive kinematics classes</li>
